      "writtenOn": "2020-01-28T22:21:12Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The only reason I implemented it this way was to retain the original behaviour as a default, which is to completely remove LD_PRELOAD from the environment after the main program is loaded.\nI did not want to change it to avoid breaking some use cases I have no idea of.\n\nNow, if as one of the maintainers you tell me that implying the \"keep\" behaviour as long as --child-ld-preload is used is fine, I can easily modify the patch this way (and adjust the documentation accordingly).\n\nIf we go this route, shall we go for the \"keep\" behaviour for both --child-ld-preload and also \"env LD_PRELOAD\u003dx.so minijail0\", or only when --child-ld-preload is used? My guess is that it would be better to only make it this way when --child-ld-preload is used, precisely to avoid changing the default behaviour of getting rid of LD_PRELOAD when the program is started, if it happens to already be set in the calling environment (maybe some use cases rely on this?).",
